      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid, or more accurately, lactate, is a byproduct of anaerobic respiration when your muscles are working harder than they can supply oxygen. It's produced when glucose is broken down without enough oxygen to complete the full aerobic process. To get it out, your body has several mechanisms, like using it as fuel for other tissues or converting it back into glucose in the liver. It's a complex process, but think of it like a quick, high-energy burst that the body has to manage afterward.",
